End period plastics¶

End period plastics initiated by Ella Daish, is a campaign to eliminate plastics in feminine hygiene products (FHP). The campaign includes meetings throughout Europe with manufactures, suppliers and vendors of plastic FHP as well as data related to the presece of these items in lakes and rivers in the region. FHP, as well as many other personal hygiene items, are a regular feature of beach litter surveys. Ella was keen to do a litter survey and collect data regarding the abundance of these objects on the shores of Lake Geneva.

Ella did have time and transportation constraints that limited her choice of survey locations:

  • access with public transport

  • seeking a specific type of object (plastic feminine hygiene products

  • preferably a location where this object has been previously identified

She summarized her preferences and constraints in the following way:

She only had three hours and would prefer to go to a place where she would likely find one.

Tampon applicators are part of a group of objects that are found on the beach that most likely originate from a toilet or a waste water treatment facility. Depending on the methods used at a water treatment facility the objects pass in between whatever system is in place for collecting inorganic solids in the waste water. This is a common problem and has been linked to older or undersized facilities.

The Challenge

Identify the location that has the greatest probability of finding a specifc object at one beach-litter survey within the defined geographic and temporal bounds given the data from the previous surveys.

The objects of interest: tampons and tampon applicators.

Geographic bounds: City of Geneva and accessible by public transport

Temporal bounds: no more than three hours including transport

The parameter that is being maximized is $\theta$, the probability of finding one FHP object at a beach-litter survey.

The probability of finding one FHP on the beach in Lac Léman¶

Historical data¶

The first sample was recorded on Lac Lman on November 23, 2015. Between November 2015 and June 2021 there were 247 beach-litter surveys. On a per sample basis, FHP were present in 102 samples (41%). In total there were 78,104 objects removed and identified, of which 358 objects were either tampons or tampon applicators (0.45%). A quick esitmate of the probability of finding one FHP on the beach could be 41%, the ratio of the number of samples where at least one FHP was found (102) to the total number of samples (227). While FHP objects are found on the lake with a probability of 41% they represent a small portion of the total inventory of objects identified.

There are three seperate sampling periods that were identified on Lac Lman. The sampling periods are not of the same length and the sampling frequency is not fixed, except for a few specific locations in period two and three. There were no samples collected in Geneva during sampling period two.

Period one: 2015-11-15 to 2017-03-01; the first project on Lac Lman (MCBP)

Period two: 2017-04-01 to 2018-05-01; the Swiss Litter Report (SLR)

Period three: 2020-03-01 to 2021-11-01; the start of IQAASL up to two weeks before the survey with Ella

Another way to estimate the probability is to assume that it falls between the minimum and maximum observed values for the different survey periods. For example, an estimate of the probability of finding an FHP (y/n) on the lake could be 34% - 71% and for Geneva 0 - 25%, see tables below.

To account for the results from prior sampling periods bayesian inference will be used to estmate the location in Geneva that may have the highest value of $\theta$ with respect to the other locations given the previous survey results.

Method¶

For each sampling period the proportion of samples that have at least one recorded instance of an FHP (y) with respect to the total number of samples (y/n), is the parameter of interest: $\theta$. Sequential Bayesian analysis is used to determine the probable values of $\theta$ given the sample results and the different sampling periods.

$$p({\theta} | y) = \frac{p(\theta)p(y | \theta)}{p(y)}$$

The distribution of y is a binomial random variable that can be summarized according to a binomial distribution.

$$ \begin{align} p(y|\theta) &= Bin(y|n,\theta)\\ &={n \choose y} \theta^y (1-\theta)^{ n-y } \end{align} $$

This sampling model was chosen because it is assumed that the the probability of finding an FHP is the same for all locations in the region of interest, Lake Geneva. To start the analysis an initial estimate of $\theta$ prior to the start of sampling must be made. {cite}bayesianDataAnalysisThird

initial estimates

When sampling started in 2015 there were no reference values for the region. Count surveys of litter data in the maritime environment had produced volumes of data but under significantly different conditions. Without reference values we had no prior assumptions on the probability of finding an FHP and assumed the probability was $\approx$ for all locations on the lake. The parameter that is being evaluated, $\theta$, is bounded by zero and one making the Beta binomial distribution with $\alpha$=1 and $\beta$=1 a fair evaluation of expectations based on the knowledge at the time.

The assumed distribution of $\theta$ prior to November 2015 is therefore $\theta \sim Beta(1,1)$. Which is a conjugate prior of the binomial distribution. This results in a closed form posterior density and predictable methods for updating the p($\theta$ | data) from one sampling period to the next.

likelihood function

The likelihood function $pr(y|n,\theta) = \theta^y (1-\theta)^{ n-y }$ is the PMF of the sampling model $Bin(y|n,\theta)$ without the factor ${n \choose y}$ because those fixed values are not dependent on the value of $\theta$. {cite}bayesianDataAnalysisThird

updating the probability

The posterior density for $\theta$ is the product of the prior distribution and the likelihood:

$$ \begin{align} \text{prior } &= \theta^{\alpha - 1}(1\theta)^{\beta - 1}\\ \text{likelihood } &= \theta^y (1-\theta)^{ n-y }\\ \text{prior * likelihood } &= \theta^{\alpha - 1 + y} (1 - \theta)^{\beta - 1 + n - y} \end{align} $$

The posterior distribution is an unormalized beta distribution with parameters $\alpha + y$ and $\beta + n - y$. This means that the prior uninformed estimate in November 2015 can be updated with the data from each sampling period in sequence. Using this method the results from sampling period one (which incorporate the initial estimate) become the prior distribution for the results of sampling period two and this process is repeated until the last sampling period. For example:

Sampling period one example

$\theta \sim Beta(1,1)$ = estimate $\theta$ prior to sampling

n - y = number of samples in period one WITHOUT an FHP

y = number of samples in period one WITH at leat one FHP

apply n and y from the observed results to the initial estimate:

$\theta \sim Beta( \beta = 1 + y, \alpha = 1 + n - y)$ = the estimated probability after period one and the prior distribution (initial estimate) for period two.

Assumptions

  • The samples are independent and identically distributed
  • $\theta$ $\approx$ for all locations which is the expected value for the lake
  • The expected result for the lake or the region is the best estimate for locations without samples

For locations that do not have samples durring a sampling period the assumed result is $\approx$ to the y, n for the lake. The results for the lake are reduced to approximate the ratio y/n without overpowering the results from individual locations:

  1. period one: y=31, n=94 $\approx$ y=1, n=3
  2. period two: y=29, n=46 $\approx$ y=3, n=5
  3. period three: y=38, n=99 $\approx$ y=2, n=5

This type of prior is intended to be informative and will have an impact on the final results. The model is repeated using using both values from the lake.

The probability of finding one FHP¶

The expected probability of finding one FHP on a beach on Lake Geneva is between 35% and 47% (95%ETI) with an expected mean of 41%. If the survey results are restricted to the City of Geneva the expected probabaiity is between 10% and 40% (95%ETI) and an expected mean of 23%.

The probability of finding an FHP at a particular beach¶

The probability of finding one FHP at a specific beach depends on the beach that is visited. Geneva is at the end of a lake and has expanded over the years to include both the left and right bank of Lac Lman. There are no survey locations at the Rhne out fall, the shoreline in this area is well developed to support structures like the Sujets Dam and Mont Blanc Bridge. As a result, the survey locations in Geneva are either on the right or left bank of the lake.

Getting from one side of the lake to the other on public transport can take up to an hour, which is 1/3 of the time allotted for the whole experiment. Therfore, a choice needs to be made as to which side of the lake to search.

An initial assessment was made for each location by dividing the number of samples with FHP by the total number of samples for each location ($\frac{y_{tot}}{n_{tot}}$). Using this method we are ignoring the values from the other samples that were collected on the same lake within the same time frame.

Figure two: map of survey results The locations in Geneva are separated by the lake and the downtown area. The value of $\frac{y_{tot}}{n_{tot}}$ for all surveys at each of the locations is given as the diameter of the marker for the locations of interest. Using this method it appears that jardin-botanique or baby-plage-geneva are the front runners.

Weak prior: $p(\theta_{geneva})$ is similar but different to $p(\theta_{lake})$

Under this Hypothesis the variance remains high for all the locations, making it difficult to choose a clear winner. However, jardin-botanique remains the front runner even though the p($\theta$) has declined from the initial estimate. The probability of not finding an FHP is greatest at villa-barton.

Figure three: Distribution of $p(\theta)$ and the probability of not finding an FHP for each location in Geneva. The posterior distribution for each sampling perriod is given, the darkest is the posterior-distribution of the last sampling period . Under this assumption the variance is relatively high and the results from local samples carry equal weight with respect to lake samples.

The distribution of $p(nonefound)$ is well defined for the locations with more samples, baby-plage-geneva and villa-barton. The locations with the fewest samples have the highest expected variance and as a result the 95% ETI of not finding an FHP includes the 95% ETI of finding one. Jardin-botanique is still a front runner given the centers of the two distributions, but the variance is high in both cases and $p(notfound)$ could likely range anywhere from 7% to 81%

Strong prior $p(\theta_{geneva})$ is $\approxeq$ to $p(\theta_{lake})$

Under the assumption that p($\theta$) in Geneva is $\approxeq$ to the rest of the lake, the variance of p($\theta$) is reduced at all locations. Because of the overwhelming number of samples on the lake, the previous local results have little effect on p($\theta$) as more sampling periods are considered. As a result the latest sample data for villa-barton (1/2 in period three) has more of an influence under this assumption than the results from the first year (1/9).

Figure four: Distribution of $p(\theta)$ and the probability of not finding an FHP for each location in Geneva. Under this assumption the expected value of $\theta$ is greater than 41% for all locations. The influence of the first sampling period on the parameters is reduced as more data is added to the model. Thus increasing effects of the most recent samples, in this instance $p(\theta)$ at villa barton increases and the early advantage of jardin-botanique is tempered by time.

Under this assumption the probability of not finding an object remains unchanged from the prior assumption. However, the 95% ETI of $p(\theta)$ is reduced and the variance is one order of magnitude less for all locations.

Discussion¶

The field operations manager, Shannon Erismann, decided that the best chances of finding an FHP was at villa-barton. Her decision was based on the proximity to the train station and the time it takes to complete a survey. Furthermore, the locations on the left bank of the lake had only 3/14 positive samples, below the mean for the lake and for Geneva. FHP had been found at villa-barton and at jardin-botanique previously (4/15) and those locations had only been sampled twice in the current period. Based on her belief that the probability of finding an FHP in Geneva was approximately the same as the lake Shannon reasoned that her chances were a little better at villa-barton.

The probability of success¶

The values of the observations (y, n) are added to the $(\alpha, \beta)$ parameters of the conjugate-prior $Beta(\alpha,\beta)$. Where n=number of samples, y=number of samples with an FHP and k=n-y, the posterior distribution of $\theta$ could be summarized as follows:

$$\theta \sim Beta(\alpha+y_{1}+y_{2}+y_{3}, \beta+k_{1}+k_{2}+k_{3})$$

Is the estimated posterior distribution of the probability of finding at least one FHP on the beach. This value of $\theta$ is not fixed therefore the probability of finding one FHP on the beach can be estimated as:

$$\theta \sim Beta(\alpha + \sum_{i=1}^{n} y_{i}, \beta + \sum_{i=1}^{n} k_{i})$$$$Y|\theta \sim Bin(n, \theta)$$

The expected value of $\theta$ is greatest either at jardin-botanique or villa-barton under the two conditions. Under the first condtion, $p(\theta_{geneva})$ is different than $p(\theta_{lake})$, the sample results from the first period are not overwhelmed by the accumulated data from the lake (figure three). Therefore the results from jardin-botanique in the first period (2/3) still have a marked effect on the posterior distribution in the last sampling period.

Under the second condition the previous results are integrated into the results from the lake, reducing the effects of the previous sampling periods. Therfore the results from villa-barton in the third period (1/2) have a greater effect on the distribution of $p(\theta)$ than those in the first period (1/10). At jardin-botanique the effect is the inverse, reducing the expected value and variance of $\theta$ making us more certain that one would be found at villa-barton if one was found at all (figure four).

The 95% ETI of not finding an FHP at villa-barton was 55% - 95% and the variance was 0.011. The lower range of the ETI is the highest of all the locations, meaning that that there was approximately a 1/2 chance that an FHP would not be found at villa-barton. One FHP was identified at villa-barton on Novemeber 14, 2021 and the experiment was completed within the allotted time.

Application¶

The EU released guidelines to calculate the median and threshold values of beach litter surveys conducted on European Seas. The results are intended to evaluate the Good environmental standing of the locations surveyed according to the Marine Strategy Framework Directive (MSFD). The threhold value for Good environmental standing was set at 20 objects of trash per 100 meters of beach, calculated to be approximately the 20th percentile of the 2015-2016 data set of beach litter surveys, the median value was approximately 133 objects per 100 meters.{cite}eubaselines

The EU threshold values are based on the observed $\frac{objects}{unit-length} = \text{rate} = r$ of a set of a collection litter surveys. A location achieves good environmental standing if the median survey result is statistically equivalent to 20/100m. If the lower range of the 95% confidence interval of the median survey value is equal to 20/100m at the end of a sampling period the location could be considered for the distinction of good environmental standing. {cite}eubaselines

Defining success in terms of survey results is a natural and inuitive method which should ensure that over time the most efficient methods will be adopted. Updating the information as new data becomes available allows stakeholders to assess the results of strategies currently in place. Therefore, determining the current probable rate of $\frac{objects}{100 meters}$ is the same as determining progress towards a goal.

Assessing changes over time¶

The students from the EPFL conduct beach litter samples each year in October and November at Saint Sulpice. The same method used to help decide which beach to go to in Geneva can be repeated year over year with the data from Saint Sulpice.

Establishing the prior data and update method

The assumption is that $\theta_{lake} \approxeq \theta_{sulpice}$ and that there will be variance between the sample locations. This assumption is the same as the prior example in Geneva. The two parameters of the beta distribution that are used to model $\theta$ need to be assessed seperately. However, not all locations within the geographic bounds were sampled at each period. In the abscence of prior data for a specific location for a given year the prior data for the lake will be used as the observed data for that year and that location.

The average value of $\theta$ for the lake prior to October 1, 2016 is the best information available reference the occurence of FHP on the beaches of Lake Geneva and is used as the prior probability distribution starting on October 1, 2016.

The rate at which objects are found¶

The eu guidelines suggest using the probability mass function (pmf) of the negative binomial distribution ( $NB$ ) estimated from survey results as a tool for determining the extreme values of a collection of litter surveys. The $NB$ is a discrete distribtution that is defined for values greater than zero. {cite}cameron {cite}eubaselines

Commonly used in situations where count data is overdispersed , the $NB$ is also known as the Gamma-Poisson mixture. The shape of the curve is defined by two parameters. In the proceeding example the distribtuion is being modeled using $n$ and $p$, according to the relationship of the probabilitiy of finding an object $p$ and the number of objects (successess) $n$ per unit length. {cite}cameron {cite}kreutshche

Once $n$ and $p$ are in hand they can be entered as parameters to the $NB$ to calculate probable values for $o$. There are several possible interpretations of the paramters of the $NB$, so many that the article on Wikepedia is tagged as contradictory. This is due to the different ways that the parameters can be calculated and wether or not success or failures are being counted over an interval. In the following example the probability mass function of the number of objects found per unit length, $o$ is defined by:

$$ f(o | \mu, \alpha) = \binom{o + \alpha - 1}{o}(\alpha/(\mu+\alpha))^\alpha (\mu/(\mu+\alpha))^o $$


$$ \text{where } \alpha > 0\text{, } 0 < p <1 \text{ and } \mu = \alpha(1-p)/p $$

The survey results can be used to estimate the likely values of $\alpha$ and $p$ so that $\mu$ can be calculated and together with $\alpha$ entered as parameters as a possible distribution of the number of FHP per 100 meters, $o$:
$$ \begin{align} P(o|\alpha, \mu) &\sim NB(\alpha, \mu)\\ \alpha &\sim Gamma(k, \theta)\\ p &\sim Beta(a, b)\\ \mu &\sim \alpha(1-p)/p\\ \end{align} $$

Ultimately the goal is to arrive at the best approximation of $\alpha$ and $\mu$, the parameters that define the shape of the probability distribution. By allowing for different values of $\alpha$ and $p$ some of the variance from the survey results can be estmated. Another method of estimating $\alpha$ and $\mu$ is to assume that they are both uniformly distributed and greater than zero. In figure five the the 90% CI for each survey is modeled using both methods. The models are confiugred and sampling is done using PyMC {cite}pymc.

Figure five: The cumulative distribution of finding an FHP on Lake Geneva. The 90% CI of finding a given quantity of FHP is in blue. The median parameter value (table 7) was used to estmate the distribtuion using Scipy.stats.nbinom, light green. The range of the 90% CI increases with the number of objects found.{cite}scipy
